    intro: "This Michigan offer in compromise calculator estimates the lowest IRS settlement Form 656-B will accept for a Michigan resident. Michigan is a common-law state, so a non-joint IRS liability generally reaches only the debtor spouse's assets. The calculator also accounts for Michigan's flat state income tax and the separate Michigan Treasury OIC program that runs parallel to the federal offer.",
    lawContext: "Michigan is not a community property state; a spouse's separately titled assets are excluded from the RCP unless the tax debt is joint. Michigan's 2026 individual income tax rate is a flat 4.25%, and Detroit adds a 2.4% resident city income tax that the IRS also treats as an allowable involuntary deduction. Michigan's state homestead exemption under MCL 600.5451 protects $46,125 of home equity ($69,200 if the debtor or a dependent is 65+ or disabled), but this is a creditor-side exemption only — the IRS values the home at 80% quick-sale value minus liens for the RCP.\n\nMichigan operates a state Offer in Compromise program that mirrors the federal one under MCL 205.23a. The Michigan Treasury accepts settlement offers on the grounds of doubt as to collectibility, doubt as to liability, or an accepted federal OIC on the same tax periods, using Form 5181. Michigan Treasury also runs aggressive levy sweeps against Michigan-source income and state refund offsets, and it will normally hold a state OIC in abeyance until any active IRS OIC is resolved, so sequencing the federal offer first is often the most efficient path.",
