    lawContext: "Missouri is not a community property state; the IRS excludes a non-liable spouse's separately titled property from the RCP on a non-joint liability. Missouri's 2026 individual income tax is graduated from 0% to a top rate of 4.7% (with additional Kansas City and St. Louis earnings taxes of 1% for residents of those cities), and the IRS allows the state liability as an involuntary deduction when it is actually being withheld or paid. Missouri's homestead creditor exemption under Mo. Rev. Stat. 513.475 protects only $15,000 of real-property equity ($5,000 for a mobile home) — one of the lowest in the country — but this exemption does not bind the IRS, which values the home at 80% quick-sale value minus liens.\n\nMissouri operates a state Offer in Compromise program administered by the Missouri Department of Revenue under Mo. Rev. Stat. 32.378, with the program using Form MO-656. The Missouri DOR accepts settlement offers on doubt as to collectibility and effective tax administration, and it typically waits for the federal OIC decision before finalizing a state offer. Missouri also enforces state tax debts via driver's-license and professional-license holds under Mo. Rev. Stat. 324.010 and 302.341, so pairing a federal OIC with a state resolution is common.",
