    h1: "Montana Offer in Compromise Calculator",
    intro: "This Montana offer in compromise calculator estimates the lowest IRS settlement Form 656-B will accept for a Montana resident. Montana is a common-law state, so a non-joint IRS liability generally reaches only the debtor spouse's assets. The calculator subtracts Montana's state income tax from remaining monthly income before applying the RCP multiplier.",
    lawContext: "Montana is not a community property state; a non-liable spouse's separately titled property is generally outside the RCP on a non-joint tax liability. Montana's 2026 individual income tax uses a simplified two-bracket structure of 4.7% and 5.9% (top rate applies above roughly $20,500 of taxable income for single filers, adjusted annually), and the IRS allows the state liability as an involuntary deduction when it is being withheld or paid. Montana's homestead exemption under Mont. Code Ann. 70-32-104 is inflation-adjusted 4% annually and reaches approximately $425,829 in 2026 (declaration required with county clerk and recorder), but that exemption does not bind the IRS, which values the home at 80% quick-sale value minus liens.\n\nMontana does NOT operate a formal statutory Offer in Compromise program for individual income tax; the Montana Department of Revenue typically handles hardship through installment agreements and case-by-case negotiated closing agreements rather than principal reduction. Montana DOR does, however, aggressively use the state-tax refund offset and wage-garnishment procedures under Mont. Code Ann. 15-1-701 et seq., and taxpayers with joint federal and state debt often use an accepted IRS OIC as leverage to negotiate a comparable Montana closing agreement.",
