    lawContext: "Oklahoma is a common-law property state (it repealed its community property statute in 1949), so a non-liable spouse's separate assets are not automatically included in Form 656 RCP. For 2026, Oklahoma uses a six-bracket structure with a top marginal rate of 4.75%, and that state tax counts as a Category 3 allowable expense on Form 433-A(OIC). Oklahoma has one of the most generous state homestead exemptions in the country — unlimited value on up to 1 acre urban or 160 acres rural under Okla. Const. Art. XII §§1–2 — but the IRS applies its own 80%-quick-sale valuation regardless.\n\nOklahoma administers the Application for Settlement of Tax Liability under 68 O.S. §219.1, filed on Form OTC-600 with supporting financial statements OTC-600-A/B/C. The Oklahoma Tax Commission may accept a settlement if collection would cause bankruptcy, the tax is uncollectible due to insolvency beyond the taxpayer's control, or the liability is attributable to another person's actions. If the savings exceed $10,000, Oklahoma County District Court approval is required. Trust taxes (sales tax, withholding) are generally not eligible unless the taxpayer proves the tax was never collected.",
